{{commonscat|Naka-hikawa-jinja (Mikajima, Tokorozawa)|Nakahikawa Shrine (Tokorozawa Mikajima)}}
'''Nakahikawa Shrine'''（なかひかわじんじゃ）is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} of the {{ill|lt=Hikawa faith|Q11549596|qid=Q11549596|1=Hikawa shinkō}} in {{ill|lt=Mikajima (Tokorozawa)|Q14085473|qid=Q14085473|lt=Mikajima|1=Mikajima}}, {{ill|lt=Tokorozawa|Q165857|qid=Q165857|1=Tokorozawa, Saitama}}, {{ill|lt=Saitama Prefecture|Q128186|qid=Q128186|1=Saitama Prefecture}}. It is the tutelary shrine of former Mikajima village and was formerly a {{ill|lt=Sonsha|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=village shrine|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}.

=== History ===
It is said to have been enshrined from Omiya Hikawa Shrine in the reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Sujin|Q333530|qid=Q333530|1=Emperor Sujin}} ({{ill|lt=97 BCE|Q41672|qid=Q41672|1=97 BC}}-{{ill|lt=29 BCE|Q40835|qid=Q40835|1=29 BC}}), and that {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Yamato Takeru|1=Yamato Takeru|qid=Q461258}} stopped here during his eastern campaign and enshrined Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto and {{ill|lt=Sukunabikona|Q3275687|qid=Q3275687|lt=Sukunahikona-no-Mikoto|1=Sukunabikona}}. Until the {{ill|lt=Muromachi period|Q334845|qid=Q334845|1=Muromachi period}} it was called "Nakamiyā," and in the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|qid=Q184963|1=Edo period}} it was called "Nagamiyā Myōjin-sha" because of its long, narrow precincts{{sfn|新編武蔵風土記稿 三ヶ島村}}. In {{ill|lt=Tenshō|Q1145058|qid=Q1145058|1=Tenshō (Momoyama period)}} 19 ({{ill|lt=1591|Q6766|qid=Q6766|1=1591}}), {{ill|lt=Tokugawa Ieyasu|Q171977|qid=Q171977|1=Tokugawa Ieyasu}} granted it shuin land. In the first year of {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}, it was renamed Nakahikawa Shrine.

Since Meiji, it has claimed to be the candidate for the Shikinaisha Nakahikawa-sha, but this has not gained strong support.

=== Buildings and precincts ===
[[File:Naka-Hikawa-jinja (Tokorozawa Mikajima) 01.jpg|thumb|220px|The torii is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=shinmei torii|1=UNKNOWN}} type]]
* A sacred {{ill|lt=zelkova|Q920344|qid=Q920344|1=Zelkova serrata}} that fell and died in a storm soon after the war has been preserved.
* There is also a poem monument for {{ill|lt=Mikajima Yoshiko|Q11354060|qid=Q11354060|1=Yoshiko Mikashima}}, a poet and daughter of a priest of this shrine.
** "Spring rain - from the hazy boughs of the oak, drops of dew glitter and fall."

=== Festivals ===
* The spring grand festival is held on April 15, and the autumn grand festival on September 29.
* A {{ill|lt=horse-back streaming race|Q1886157|qid=Q1886157|1=Yabusame}} ritual used to be held on the long approach, but it has ceased.

=== Cultural properties ===
* Bronze triad hanging Buddha: designated cultural property of Tokorozawa (Tangible Cultural Property / Craftwork){{sfn|所沢市の指定文化財}}.
* Nichikarin-ō-no-hi monument: designated cultural property of Tokorozawa (Tangible Cultural Property / Historical Material){{sfn|所沢市の指定文化財}}.

=== Location and access ===
* Mikajima 5-1691-1, Tokorozawa, Saitama Prefecture
** From {{ill|lt=Kotesashi Station|Q6433936|qid=Q6433936|1=Kotesashi Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Seibu Ikebukuro Line|Q93546|qid=Q93546|1=Seibu Ikebukuro Line}}, take {{ill|lt=Seibu Bus|Q11628880|qid=Q11628880|1=Seibu Bus}} route {{ill|lt=Kote 04/06|Q11628891|qid=Q11628891|1=Kote 04/06}}, get off at Horinouchi.

